                  <h1><span style="font-size: 22px;">US State Championship Bowl</span></h1>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p style="margin-left: 2em;">Location:<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>Strong Players</p>
                  <p style="margin-left: 2em;">Eligibility:<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>Open to 2023 State Champions and other major tournament winners (see additional details below)*</p>
                  <p style="margin-left: 2em;">Director(s):<span>&nbsp;Steve Zhang</span></p>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p>This a competition between all the state champions for the previous year to settle who is the <strong>US State Champ</strong>! </p>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p><strong>Format:</strong> “Knockout” tournament consisting of several rounds in the afternoons (e.g. Mon, Tue, Thurs, Fri).  The number of rounds depends on the number of entrants. </p>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p><strong>Time Limit:</strong> The limit is 60 minutes per player. The overtime byo-yomi allotment will be 5 periods of 30 seconds each.</p>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p><strong>Rules:</strong> AGA rules should be used. Komi for white is 7.5 points.</p>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p><strong>Handicaps: </strong>All games are to be played even.</p>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p><strong>Prizes:</strong> The final winner will be crowned US State Champion and will receive both a trophy cup and prize of $1,000.  The second-place winner will receive $500.</p>
                  <p>&nbsp;</p>
                  <p><strong>*Eligibility:</strong> To play, you must be a resident of the state where the tournament occurred, and when it was held. If there wasn't a champion from your state in 2023, the 2022 champion can participate. <br><br>
                  Since this is a new tournament just getting started, we’re also allowing a winner of a major tournament in a state which didn’t have an official Championship.  If the winner of a major tournament was not a resident of the state, we will also accept the next highest placing resident of the state. </p>
